================================================================================
 1. REQUIREMENTS
================================================================================

  Cacti Version       1.2.0 or later (1.2.24+ recommended)
  PHP Version         7.4 or later (8.0+ recommended)
  Database            MySQL 5.7+ / MariaDB 10.2+

  Required PHP Extensions:
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    gmp               IPv4/IPv6 address math (plugin will NOT load without it)

  Recommended PHP Extensions:
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    sockets            TCP network scanning (Professional+ license)
    curl               Webhook callbacks (Enterprise license)
    snmp               DHCP scope monitoring and ARP scanning (Enterprise)
    gd / imagick       PDF report generation (Professional+)

  Optional External Tools:
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    fping              Fast ICMP ping sweep for network scanning
                       (falls back to TCP scanning if unavailable)

  Optional Cacti Plugins:
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    cereus_license     License validation for Professional/Enterprise tiers.
                       Without it the plugin runs in Community mode (free).
    restapi            Required only for REST API endpoints (Enterprise).

================================================================================
 2. INSTALLATION ON LINUX (Apache / Nginx)
================================================================================

  2.1  Extract the Plugin
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    cd /var/www/html/cacti/plugins/
    tar xzf cereus_ipam-1.0.0.tar.gz

    -- or clone from GitHub --

    cd /var/www/html/cacti/plugins/
    git clone https://github.com/thurban/plugin_cereus_ipam.git cereus_ipam

  2.2  Install Required PHP Extensions
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    Debian / Ubuntu:
      apt install php-gmp php-sockets php-curl php-snmp

    RHEL / Rocky / AlmaLinux (with Remi repository):
      dnf install php-gmp php-sockets php-curl php-snmp

    After installing, restart your web server:

      systemctl restart httpd        # Apache on RHEL
      systemctl restart apache2      # Apache on Debian
      systemctl restart nginx        # Nginx (also restart php-fpm)
      systemctl restart php-fpm

  2.3  Set File Ownership
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    The plugin directory must be owned by the web server user.

    RHEL / Rocky / AlmaLinux (Apache):
      chown -R apache:apache /var/www/html/cacti/plugins/cereus_ipam/

    Debian / Ubuntu (Apache):
      chown -R www-data:www-data /var/www/html/cacti/plugins/cereus_ipam/

    Nginx (typically):
      chown -R nginx:nginx /var/www/html/cacti/plugins/cereus_ipam/

  2.4  Install fping (Optional, for ICMP Scanning)
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    fping is used for fast ICMP-based network scanning from the Cacti poller.
    If fping is not installed, the plugin falls back to TCP-based scanning
    which works everywhere without special permissions.

    Debian / Ubuntu:
      apt install fping

    RHEL / Rocky / AlmaLinux:
      dnf install fping

    Verify:
      which fping          # Should return /usr/sbin/fping or /usr/bin/fping
      fping --version

    Note: fping requires raw socket capability. When run from the Cacti
    poller (CLI as root or cacti user), this is typically available. From
    the web UI, fping is NOT used — the plugin automatically falls back to
    TCP scanning in the web context.

  2.5  Enable the Plugin in Cacti
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    1. Log in to Cacti as an administrator.
    2. Navigate to Configuration > Plugins.
    3. Find "Cereus IPAM" in the list and click "Install".
    4. After installation, click "Enable".
    5. Navigate to Configuration > Settings > Cereus IPAM to configure.
    6. Grant users access: Configuration > Users > (user) > Realm Permissions
       > check "Plugin: Cereus IPAM - Manage".

================================================================================
 3. INSTALLATION ON WINDOWS (IIS)
================================================================================

  3.1  Prerequisites
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    - Cacti for Windows installed and functional (see Cacti documentation)
    - PHP installed as FastCGI under IIS (PHP 7.4+ or 8.0+)
    - MySQL or MariaDB installed and accessible

  3.2  Extract the Plugin
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    Extract the plugin archive to Cacti's plugins directory:

      C:\inetpub\wwwroot\cacti\plugins\cereus_ipam\

    Ensure the directory structure is:

      C:\inetpub\wwwroot\cacti\plugins\cereus_ipam\setup.php
      C:\inetpub\wwwroot\cacti\plugins\cereus_ipam\INFO
      C:\inetpub\wwwroot\cacti\plugins\cereus_ipam\lib\
      C:\inetpub\wwwroot\cacti\plugins\cereus_ipam\includes\
      ...

    Note: Adjust the base path if your Cacti installation is in a different
    location (e.g. C:\Cacti\plugins\cereus_ipam\).

  3.3  Enable Required PHP Extensions
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    Open your php.ini file (typically C:\PHP\php.ini or wherever PHP is
    installed) and ensure the following extensions are uncommented:

      extension=gmp             ; REQUIRED - IPv4/IPv6 math
      extension=sockets         ; Recommended - TCP network scanning
      extension=curl            ; Recommended - Webhook support
      extension=snmp            ; Recommended - DHCP/ARP scanning

    After editing php.ini, restart IIS:

      iisreset

    To verify the extensions are loaded, open a command prompt:

      php -m | findstr gmp
      php -m | findstr sockets

    Or check phpinfo() output via Cacti's Utilities > Technical Support.

  3.4  Install fping for Windows (Optional)
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    fping is available for Windows as a third-party build. If you want
    ICMP-based scanning from the poller (faster than TCP for large subnets):

    1. Download fping for Windows (e.g. from the Cacti forums or
       https://github.com/schweikert/fping — Windows builds may be
       community-provided).

    2. Place fping.exe in a known location, for example:

         C:\fping\fping.exe

    3. In Cacti, configure the path under:
       Configuration > Settings > Cereus IPAM > fping Path

       Enter:  C:\fping\fping.exe

    If fping is not installed, the plugin uses TCP-based scanning which
    works without any external tools. For most Windows deployments, TCP
    scanning is the recommended approach.

  3.5  IIS File Permissions
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    The IIS application pool identity (typically IIS_IUSRS or the
    application pool's virtual account) must have read access to the
    plugin directory.

    Using icacls from an elevated Command Prompt:

      icacls "C:\inetpub\wwwroot\cacti\plugins\cereus_ipam" /grant "IIS_IUSRS:(OI)(CI)R" /T

    If your application pool runs under a specific identity (e.g.
    "IIS AppPool\Cacti"), use that instead:

      icacls "C:\inetpub\wwwroot\cacti\plugins\cereus_ipam" /grant "IIS AppPool\Cacti:(OI)(CI)R" /T

    The temp directory must also be writable for CSV report generation:

      icacls "%TEMP%" /grant "IIS_IUSRS:(OI)(CI)M"

  3.6  IIS URL Rewrite (if applicable)
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    Cereus IPAM does not require URL rewriting. All pages are accessed
    directly via their .php filenames through Cacti's navigation. No
    web.config rules are needed for the plugin itself.

  3.7  Enable the Plugin in Cacti
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    Follow the same steps as section 2.5 above:

    1. Configuration > Plugins > Install "Cereus IPAM"
    2. Enable the plugin
    3. Configure under Configuration > Settings > Cereus IPAM
    4. Grant user permissions via Realm Permissions

================================================================================
 4. POST-INSTALL CONFIGURATION
================================================================================

  After enabling the plugin, navigate to:

    Configuration > Settings > Cereus IPAM

  4.1  General Settings
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    Enabled (cereus_ipam_enabled)
      Master switch. Default: On.

    Device Sync (cereus_ipam_device_sync)
      Automatically link Cacti devices to IPAM addresses by matching
      hostnames/IPs. Runs every poller cycle. Default: On.

  4.2  Network Scanning (Professional+ License)
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    Scheduled Scanning (cereus_ipam_scan_enabled)
      Enable automatic scanning of subnets on their configured intervals.
      Default: Off.

    Max Concurrent Scans (cereus_ipam_scan_concurrent)
      Maximum subnets to scan simultaneously per poller cycle.
      Default: 5.

    Scan Method (cereus_ipam_scan_method)
      - Auto:  Uses fping from CLI/poller (fastest), TCP from web UI.
               On Windows, uses fping.exe if available, otherwise TCP.
      - fping: Forces fping for all contexts (may fail from web UI).
      - TCP:   Parallel non-blocking TCP connect. Works on all platforms
               without special permissions. Default: Auto.

    fping Path (cereus_ipam_fping_path)
      Leave empty for auto-detection. The plugin searches:
      - Linux:   /usr/sbin/fping, /usr/bin/fping, /usr/local/*/fping,
                 and Cacti's configured fping path.
      - Windows: C:\fping\fping.exe, Cacti base path, and PATH dirs.

    TCP Probe Ports (cereus_ipam_scan_tcp_ports)
      Comma-separated TCP ports for host detection. Tried in order; stops
      at first alive response. Default: 80,443,22.

    Scan Timeout (cereus_ipam_scan_timeout)
      Timeout per scan batch in milliseconds (100-30000). Default: 2000.

  4.3  Alert Settings (Professional+ License)
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    Threshold Alerts: Email warnings when subnet utilization exceeds the
    configured percentage. Uses Cacti's mail subsystem.

    Conflict Alerts: Email warnings when IP conflicts are detected (MAC
    mismatch, rogue IPs, stale addresses).

    Both support manual email addresses and/or Cacti notification lists.
    Cooldown prevents alert spam (default: 86400 seconds / 24 hours).

  4.4  Scheduled Reports (Professional+ License)
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    Automated email reports with CSV attachments covering utilization,
    address states, and stale address listings.

    Frequency: daily, weekly (default), or monthly.

  4.5  Webhooks (Enterprise License)
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    POST JSON event payloads to external URLs on subnet/address changes.
    Configure one URL per line. 5-second timeout per request.
    Test button available on the settings page.

================================================================================
 5. PHP EXTENSION REFERENCE
================================================================================

  +------------+----------+--------------------------------------------------+
  | Extension  | Status   | Purpose                                          |
  +------------+----------+--------------------------------------------------+
  | gmp        | REQUIRED | All IPv4/IPv6 address calculations. Plugin will  |
  |            |          | not load without this extension.                 |
  +------------+----------+--------------------------------------------------+
  | sockets    | Recomm.  | TCP-based network scanning. Required for the TCP |
  |            |          | scan method (Professional+ feature). Not needed  |
  |            |          | if using fping exclusively.                      |
  +------------+----------+--------------------------------------------------+
  | curl       | Recomm.  | Webhook callbacks to external URLs (Enterprise). |
  |            |          | Not needed if webhooks are not used.              |
  +------------+----------+--------------------------------------------------+
  | snmp       | Recomm.  | ARP table scanning via SNMP and DHCP scope       |
  |            |          | monitoring (Enterprise). Uses Cacti's built-in   |
  |            |          | SNMP functions.                                  |
  +------------+----------+--------------------------------------------------+

  Linux quick-check:
    php -m | grep -E "gmp|sockets|curl|snmp"

  Windows quick-check:
    php -m | findstr "gmp sockets curl snmp"

  Or in Cacti: Utilities > Technical Support > PHP Module Information.

================================================================================
 6. SECURITY: SELinux (RHEL / Rocky / AlmaLinux)
================================================================================

  If SELinux is enabled (enforcing mode), the following considerations apply.

  6.1  Web UI Access (httpd_t context)
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    The plugin's PHP files run under the httpd_t SELinux context. The
    following operations are handled automatically:

    - Database access:  Allowed via httpd_can_network_connect_db
    - TCP scanning:     Works under httpd_t (uses PHP sockets, no raw
                        sockets needed)
    - DNS resolution:   Allowed natively
    - Webhook calls:    Requires httpd_can_network_connect

    Enable network connectivity for outbound webhook/email calls:

      setsebool -P httpd_can_network_connect on

    This is typically already enabled if Cacti sends email or uses
    Thold/notification plugins.

  6.2  Poller Context (unconfined_t or cacti_t)
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    The Cacti poller (cron/systemd) typically runs as root or the cacti
    user under unconfined_t, which has no restrictions.

    fping requires raw sockets (CAP_NET_RAW). When run from the poller
    as root, this is available. If the poller runs as a non-root user:

      # Option A: Set capability on fping binary
      setcap cap_net_raw+ep /usr/sbin/fping

      # Option B: Set SUID bit (less recommended)
      chmod u+s /usr/sbin/fping

    Note: From the web UI, fping is NEVER used. The plugin automatically
    falls back to TCP scanning in the web context, which requires no
    special capabilities.

  6.3  File Context Labels
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    Plugin files should have the httpd_sys_content_t label. If you
    extracted the plugin from a tarball or Git, restore the labels:

      restorecon -Rv /var/www/html/cacti/plugins/cereus_ipam/

    Verify:
      ls -Z /var/www/html/cacti/plugins/cereus_ipam/setup.php
      # Should show: system_u:object_r:httpd_sys_content_t:s0

  6.4  SELinux Quick Reference
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    Check current mode:
      getenforce

    Check relevant booleans:
      getsebool httpd_can_network_connect
      getsebool httpd_can_network_connect_db

    If you encounter "Permission denied" errors in the Cacti log, check
    the SELinux audit log:
      ausearch -m avc -ts recent | grep cereus_ipam

================================================================================
 7. SECURITY: FIREWALL SETTINGS
================================================================================

  7.1  Inbound (to the Cacti Server)
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    No additional inbound ports are required. The plugin uses Cacti's
    existing web interface (typically port 80/443).

    If you have the REST API plugin (Enterprise) and expose it externally,
    ensure your existing Cacti web port rules apply.

  7.2  Outbound (from the Cacti Server)
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    The plugin may need outbound connectivity for the following features:

    +------------------+------------+----------------------------------------+
    | Feature          | Port/Proto | Destination                            |
    +------------------+------------+----------------------------------------+
    | Email alerts     | TCP 25/587 | Your SMTP server (uses Cacti's mailer) |
    | Webhook calls    | TCP 80/443 | Configured webhook URLs (Enterprise)   |
    | SNMP ARP scan    | UDP 161    | Cacti-monitored devices                |
    | SNMP DHCP poll   | UDP 161    | DHCP servers (Enterprise)              |
    | DNS resolution   | UDP 53     | DNS server (for reverse lookups)       |
    | fping ICMP sweep | ICMP       | Target subnets (if fping is used)      |
    | TCP scan         | TCP *      | Target subnets on configured ports     |
    |                  |            | (default: 80, 443, 22)                 |
    +------------------+------------+----------------------------------------+

    Linux (firewalld):

      # Email (if not already open):
      firewall-cmd --permanent --add-port=25/tcp
      firewall-cmd --permanent --add-port=587/tcp

      # ICMP (for fping, typically already allowed):
      firewall-cmd --permanent --add-icmp-block-inversion

      # Reload:
      firewall-cmd --reload

    Linux (iptables):

      # Allow outbound ICMP for fping:
      iptables -A OUTPUT -p icmp --icmp-type echo-request -j ACCEPT

      # Allow outbound TCP for scanning:
      iptables -A OUTPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT
      iptables -A OUTPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j ACCEPT
      iptables -A OUTPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j ACCEPT

    Windows Firewall (PowerShell, elevated):

      # Allow outbound ICMP for fping:
      New-NetFirewallRule -DisplayName "Cacti IPAM ICMP" `
        -Direction Outbound -Protocol ICMPv4 -Action Allow

      # Allow outbound TCP scanning (if needed):
      New-NetFirewallRule -DisplayName "Cacti IPAM TCP Scan" `
        -Direction Outbound -Protocol TCP `
        -RemotePort 22,80,443 -Action Allow

    Note: Most server firewalls allow outbound connections by default.
    These rules are only needed if your firewall has a restrictive
    outbound policy.

================================================================================
 8. SECURITY: FILE PERMISSIONS
================================================================================

  8.1  Linux
  ~~~~~~~~~~

    All plugin files should be owned by the web server user and be
    read-only. No files need write access.

      chown -R apache:apache /var/www/html/cacti/plugins/cereus_ipam/
      find /var/www/html/cacti/plugins/cereus_ipam/ -type f -exec chmod 644 {} \;
      find /var/www/html/cacti/plugins/cereus_ipam/ -type d -exec chmod 755 {} \;

    Replace "apache:apache" with your web server user (www-data, nginx).

  8.2  Windows
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~

    The IIS application pool identity needs Read & Execute permissions.
    No Write permissions are needed on the plugin directory.

      icacls "C:\inetpub\wwwroot\cacti\plugins\cereus_ipam" /grant "IIS_IUSRS:(OI)(CI)RX" /T

    The system temp directory must be writable for CSV report generation:

      icacls "%SystemRoot%\Temp" /grant "IIS_IUSRS:(OI)(CI)M"

================================================================================
 9. OPTIONAL COMPONENTS
================================================================================

  9.1  Cereus License Manager Plugin
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    For Professional or Enterprise features, install the Cereus License
    Manager plugin:

      https://github.com/thurban/plugin_cereus_license

    Without the license plugin, Cereus IPAM runs in Community mode with:
    - 10 subnet limit
    - IPv4 only
    - CSV import limited to 500 rows
    - 30-day changelog retention
    - No scheduled scanning, VLANs, VRFs, custom fields, reports,
      webhooks, DHCP monitoring, or multi-tenancy

  9.2  REST API Plugin (Enterprise)
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    For REST API access to IPAM data, install the Cereus REST API plugin.
    Cereus IPAM automatically registers its endpoints when both plugins
    are active.

    Endpoints registered:
    - GET/POST /ipam/sections
    - GET/POST /ipam/subnets
    - GET/POST /ipam/addresses
    - GET      /ipam/vlans
    - GET      /ipam/vrfs
    - POST     /ipam/scan/{subnet_id}

  9.3  fping Binary
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    fping provides faster ICMP-based scanning compared to TCP probing.
    It is most useful for large subnets (/22 and bigger) where TCP
    scanning may be slower.

    The plugin automatically detects whether fping is available and
    falls back to TCP scanning if it is not. TCP scanning works on all
    platforms without any external tools or special permissions.

    Performance comparison (typical /24 subnet, 256 hosts):
    - fping:        ~2-3 seconds
    - TCP parallel: ~3-5 seconds (depends on configured timeout)

================================================================================
 10. LICENSE ACTIVATION
================================================================================

  If you have purchased a Professional or Enterprise license:

  1. Install the Cereus License Manager plugin (see section 9.1).
  2. Navigate to Configuration > Settings > Cereus License.
  3. Paste your license key in the "Cereus IPAM" field.
  4. Click Save. The license status will update immediately.
  5. Verify under Configuration > Settings > Cereus IPAM — the header
     will show "Professional License" or "Enterprise License".

  License tiers unlock the following features:

  +----------------------+-----------+--------------+------------+
  | Feature              | Community | Professional | Enterprise |
  +----------------------+-----------+--------------+------------+
  | Subnets              | 10        | Unlimited    | Unlimited  |
  | IPv6 Support         |           | Yes          | Yes        |
  | VLANs / VRFs         |           | Yes          | Yes        |
  | Custom Fields        |           | Yes          | Yes        |
  | Network Scanning     | Manual/TCP| Scheduled    | Scheduled  |
  | ARP/SNMP Scanning    |           | Yes          | Yes        |
  | Threshold Alerts     |           | Yes          | Yes        |
  | Conflict Detection   |           | Yes          | Yes        |
  | Reports / PDF        |           | Yes          | Yes        |
  | Scheduled Reports    |           | Yes          | Yes        |
  | Regex Search         |           | Yes          | Yes        |
  | RBAC per Section     |           | Yes          | Yes        |
  | Bulk IP Fill         |           | Yes          | Yes        |
  | NAT Mapping          |           | Yes          | Yes        |
  | LDAP/AD RBAC         |           |              | Yes        |
  | Multi-Tenancy        |           |              | Yes        |
  | Maintenance Windows  |           |              | Yes        |
  | DHCP Monitoring      |           |              | Yes        |
  | Webhooks             |           |              | Yes        |
  | REST API             |           |              | Yes        |
  | Rack/Locations       |           |              | Yes        |
  | Capacity Forecasting |           |              | Yes        |
  | Reconciliation       |           |              | Yes        |
  +----------------------+-----------+--------------+------------+

================================================================================
 11. UPGRADING
================================================================================

  1. Disable the plugin in Cacti: Configuration > Plugins > Disable.
  2. Back up the plugin directory and your database.
  3. Replace the plugin files with the new version.
  4. Restore file ownership (see section 8).
  5. Enable the plugin: Configuration > Plugins > Enable.
  6. The plugin will automatically run any necessary database migrations
     on the next poller cycle.

  Database tables are never dropped during upgrades. New columns are
  added via ALTER TABLE statements that check for existence first.

================================================================================
 12. TROUBLESHOOTING
================================================================================

  12.1  Plugin Does Not Appear in Plugin List
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    - Verify the directory name is exactly "cereus_ipam" (case-sensitive
      on Linux).
    - Verify setup.php and INFO files exist in the plugin directory.
    - Check Cacti log for PHP errors: Utilities > View Cacti Log.

  12.2  Plugin Fails to Install / "Check Configuration" Error
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    - The PHP GMP extension is missing. Install it and restart PHP/web
      server (see section 5).
    - Check: php -m | grep gmp

  12.3  Network Scanning Returns No Results
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    - Verify the PHP sockets extension is loaded (for TCP scanning).
    - If using fping, verify it is installed and the path is correct:
        fping -v
    - Check that outbound ICMP or TCP traffic is not blocked by a
      firewall (see section 7).
    - On SELinux systems, ensure httpd_can_network_connect is enabled
      (see section 6.1).
    - Try changing scan method to "TCP" in settings as a test.

  12.4  Emails Not Sending (Alerts / Reports)
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    - Verify Cacti's mail configuration under Configuration > Settings >
      Mail / Reporting / DNS.
    - Send a test email from Cacti's settings page.
    - Check the Cacti log for mailer errors.

  12.5  Webhooks Not Firing
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    - Verify the PHP curl extension is loaded.
    - Verify httpd_can_network_connect is enabled (SELinux).
    - Use the "Test" button on the settings page to verify connectivity.
    - Check the Cacti log for webhook errors.

  12.6  Permission Denied Errors on Linux
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    - Check file ownership: ls -la plugins/cereus_ipam/
    - Restore SELinux labels: restorecon -Rv plugins/cereus_ipam/
    - Check SELinux audit log: ausearch -m avc -ts recent

  12.7  Permission Denied Errors on Windows
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    - Check IIS application pool identity permissions (see section 3.5).
    - Verify temp directory is writable (see section 8.2).
    - Check Windows Event Viewer > Application log for PHP errors.

  12.8  Slow Scanning Performance
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

    - Install fping for ICMP scanning (faster than TCP for large subnets).
    - Reduce the TCP scan timeout (default: 2000ms) if hosts respond
      quickly on your network.
    - Reduce the number of concurrent scans if the poller is overloaded.
    - Consider scanning during off-peak hours via per-subnet schedules.

